To save data to localStorage in JavaScript, you can use the `localStorage` object. Here's an example of how to save a string to localStorage:
```
// Save a string to localStorage
const myString = "Hello, world!";
localStorage.setItem("my-string", myString);

// Read back from localStorage
const retrievedString = localStorage.getItem("my-string");
console.log(retrievedString); // Output: Hello, world!
```
You can also save objects to localStorage by using `JSON.stringify()` to convert the object to a string before saving it, and then using `JSON.parse()` to convert the string back into an object when you retrieve it from localStorage. Here's an example of how to do this:
```
// Save an object to localStorage
const myObject = { name: "John", age: 30 };
localStorage.setItem("my-object", JSON.stringify(myObject));

// Read back from localStorage
const retrievedObject = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("my-object"));
console.log(retrievedObject); // Output: { name: "John", age: 30 }
```
Note that localStorage is a key-value store, so you need to use unique keys to save multiple values. You can also use `localStorage.removeItem()` to remove an item from localStorage.
